  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. Global Standards and Recommendations\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards\n- Provides recommendations for national anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks\n- Countries are expected to implement these guidelines in their domestic legal systems\n\n2. Treaty Obligations\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism\n- These treaties create legal obligations for signatory states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Information Sharing\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Cross-border cooperation between law enforcement agencies\n- Facilitates investigation and prosecution of money laundering cases\n\n4. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international AML regulations\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) and Customer Due Diligence (CDD) protocols\n- Reporting suspicious transactions across jurisdictions\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing\n- Extradition agreements\n\n6. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Increasingly standardized legal definitions\n- Similar reporting and compliance requirements across jurisdictions\n\nThese intersections create a complex but interconnected global approach to combating money laundering.",
